{"schema_version": 2, "source_hash": "3541d4bed9bb45c0", "candidate": {"id": "cand-019", "name": "Ananya Krishnan", "raw_cv": "ANANYA KRISHNAN\nananya.krishnan@email.com | Cambridge, UK\n\nML ENGINEER\n\nPROFESSIONAL SUMMARY\nML engineer with 4 years of experience in audio and signal processing ML systems, transitioning into computer vision. Proficient in Python and PyTorch. Experience with MLflow and production model deployment.\n\nEXPERIENCE\n\nML Engineer \u2014 Sonos, Cambridge (2021\u2013present)\n- Built and deployed audio classification models for Sonos device wake-word and noise cancellation features\n- Developed training pipelines in PyTorch and managed experiments with MLflow\n- Optimised models for embedded deployment using ONNX and quantisation techniques\n- Collaborated with hardware team on latency and memory budgets\n\nGraduate ML Engineer \u2014 BT Research, Ipswich (2020\u20132021)\n- Developed speech quality assessment models for VoIP network monitoring\n\nSKILLS\nPython, PyTorch, ONNX, MLflow, NumPy, librosa, torchaudio, OpenCV (basic), Git, Docker\n\nEDUCATION\nMSc Acoustic Engineering \u2014 University of Southampton (2019\u20132020)\nBEng Electronic Engineering \u2014 University of Southampton (2016\u20132019)\n\nRIGHT TO WORK\nBritish citizen (Indian heritage)", "raw_linkedin": "ML engineer at Sonos building audio intelligence systems. Four years of experience in deep learning for audio \u2014 wake word detection, noise cancellation, speech quality. Strong PyTorch and ONNX skills, significant experience with embedded deployment and latency optimisation. Cambridge-based. Interested in broadening into computer vision and sensor-based perception systems. Open to roles in defence, IoT, or robotics.", "raw_interview_transcript": "Interviewer: Ananya, your audio ML background is interesting \u2014 how do you see yourself adapting to optical and radar-based perception?\n\nAnanya: The engineering fundamentals are very similar \u2014 both involve signal processing, CNN-based feature extraction, and hard latency constraints for embedded deployment. I've been actively studying computer vision: I completed the Stanford CS231n materials last year and I've been working on a personal project with object detection on edge hardware. My audio expertise gives me a strong foundation in signal processing that's directly relevant to radar.\n\nInterviewer: How do you feel about the hybrid setup? Two days in Cambridge.\n\nAnanya: Perfect. I live in Cambridge, I actually cycle to Sonos's office already. The hybrid model would work very well.\n\nInterviewer: Security clearance \u2014 do you hold any clearance?\n\nAnanya: I don't hold formal clearance currently. I've worked on some BT Research projects that involved government contracts with data handling agreements, but nothing that required formal SC or DV vetting. I'm a UK citizen, no dual nationality, no foreign connections \u2014 I'd expect to be eligible for clearance.\n\nInterviewer: We can sponsor that. Salary?\n\nAnanya: I'm at \u00a372,000 at Sonos. I'm looking for \u00a380\u201390,000 for this step, given the domain stretch and the defence sector context.", "years_experience": 4.0, "skills": ["Python", "PyTorch", "ONNX", "MLflow", "NumPy", "librosa", "torchaudio", "OpenCV", "Git", "Docker", "Signal Processing", "Audio ML", "Computer Vision", "Embedded Deployment", "Quantisation", "Speech Quality Assessment", "Wake-word Detection", "Noise Cancellation", "CNN Feature Extraction", "Object Detection", "Edge Hardware", "Radar Processing"], "industries": ["Audio Intelligence", "Consumer Electronics", "Telecommunications", "Defence", "IoT", "Robotics"], "seniority_level": "mid", "management_experience": false, "education_level": "master", "career_trajectory": "ascending", "interview_score": 0.85, "culture_fit_score": 0.82, "constraints": [{"id": "ff005a84", "type": "hard", "side": "candidate", "category": "compensation", "description": "Current salary at Sonos: \u00a372,000", 